default              
defaultJill Morris:default All of the cases that you have mentioned have something in common, of course, which is a bilateral dispute, particularly a sovereignty dispute, that has been imported, if you like, into the EU. So it creates a friction and a problem. But the solutions to those cases are very different, because of their very different natures. 
default              
defaultThe allergy within the EU, particularly for the Commission, to getting involved in so-called bilateral disputes has only grown. So, one of our challenges is to explain to the Commission how 
defaultthey might helpfully—from our perspective—get involved, and what they might do that would be very dangerous, in terms of entering into or becoming actors in a sovereignty dispute. So, yes, there are those analogies, but I find it difficult to see what we could learn from, for example, the 
defaultMacedonia
default name dispute; except that it is intractable and very difficult. 
default&#xa0;
